name: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3550
Reason: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate has a melting point that can be predicted by considering its structural components: (1) The basic unit we can compare to is 1-methylcyclohexane, which has a melting point of around 30 degrees Celsius. (2) The methyl group adds approximately +10 due to increasing the molecular weight and rigidity of the structure. (3) The oxo group (–O–) introduces a significant dipole moment, raising the melting point by approximately +20. (4) The androstane ring (C1C(C)CC2C3CC=C4CC(OC(=O)C)CCC4(C)C3CCC12C) adds approximately +30 due to increasing the molecular weight and rigidity of the structure. Summing these modifications gives us an estimated melting point shift.
